ve connector consistent with vent-to-surface transfer).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV cyanide-water chemistry to formamide and HCN reservoir\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, evaporitic concentration, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydrolysis/rearrangement of cyanide-derived species furnishes formamide as a concentrated nitrile-derived feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN-derived photochemistry and formamide chemistry are widely considered important in surface prebiotic synthesis, especially under UV-active, anoxic conditions with photocatalytic minerals (Saladino et al., 2012; Sutherland, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN photochemical regeneration\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photolysis and drying-rehydration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photolytic fragmentation and dehydration of formamide-containing mixtures regenerate cyanide-bearing species including HCN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Surface photochemical networks interconvert cyanide and formamide pools, sustaining cyanide-rich feedstocks used in Strecker and nucleobase chemistry (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO/CO2-H2 vent chemistry, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-bound reduced C1 fragments undergo C-C coupling and partial oxygenation to yield a C2 aldehyde, glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and related hydrothermal mineral catalysis can generate small oxygenated organics including aldehydes from reduced carbon feedstocks; glycolaldehyde as a vent-derived or vent-compatible C2 intermediate is plausible though product distributions vary (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose/aldol step to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles, mildly alkaline evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose chemistry couples formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to triose products, with borate stabilizing sugar intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Borate-stabilized sugar formation from formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde is a classic route to trioses, and clays can concentrate organics during wet-dry cycles (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent gradients, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive carboxylation and C-C assembly of activated acetyl/acetate-like intermediates generate the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate and related central metabolites have been reported or proposed from nonenzymatic CO2 fixation and iron-catalyzed protometabolic networks under hydrothermal conditions (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent pore setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-mediated reduction yields alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a key prebiotic route to amino acids, especially in iron-sulfur settings (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration, anoxic, intermittent drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia and HCN through aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker synthesis is one of the most established prebiotic amino acid-forming reactions and is especially plausible in cyanide-rich surface pools (Miller, 1957; Powner et al., 2009 for cyanide-rich prebiotic context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation/hydration of glyceraldehyde to glycerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted redox in shallow pools, wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Triose aldehyde undergoes oxidation/hydration to the corresponding hydroxy acid glycerate, aided by mineral-mediated photoredox and phosphate buffering.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Photochemical and phosphate-assisted transformations among sugar and sugar-acid pools are plausible in surface geochemical settings; this step is a reasonable connector between formose products and serine precursors, though less directly constrained than Strecker chemistry (Pasek & Kee, 2011; speculative connector consistent with UV-photoredox surface chemistry).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide-assisted conversion of glycolaldehyde to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich pool with hydrolysis after aminonitrile formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde undergoes Strecker-like cyanation with ammonia to a beta-hydroxyl aminonitrile followed by hydrolysis to serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Serine can arise prebiotically from beta-hydroxyl carbonyl compounds by Strecker-type chemistry; using glycolaldehyde as precursor is plausible in cyanide-rich surface settings, though direct yield data are less extensive than for glycine and alanine (Miller, 1957; speculative extension of Strecker chemistry needed for target completion).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination and hydroxymethylation network to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interfaces\", \"lipid membranes\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pools, geothermal cycling, wet-dry selection, compartmentalization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A network-level step representing nonenzymatic interconversion of alpha-keto acids, hydroxy acids, aldehydes, and amino acids through transamination, aldol addition, hydroxymethyl transfer, and selective hydrolysis to yield serine from multiple precursor combinations.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nonenzymatic protometabolic systems can interconvert pyruvate, amino acids, sugar-derived aldehydes, and hydroxy acids; serine is plausibly accessed from glycerate-like and hydroxymethylated glycine-like intermediates in mixed prebiotic pools. Exact one-pot conversion remains incompletely resolved, so this node explicitly represents a literature-consistent but partially integrative biochemical assembly stage (Muchowska et al., 2019; Kitadai et al., 2018; speculative network-integration step).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct glycolaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C2 aldehyde formation followed by surface Strecker-like conversion gives serine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-formaldehyde-glycolaldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived formate is reduced to formaldehyde, combined into glycolaldehyde, then converted to serine on the surface.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-to-glyceraldehyde-to-serine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 and C2 inputs feed borate-stabilized surface triose synthesis, then biochemical conversion to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycerate-mediated sugar acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface glyceraldehyde is oxidized to glycerate, which enters biochemical transamination/hydroxymethylation chemistry to yield serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to serine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent pyruvate feeds a later biochemical network that also uses C1/C2 sugar intermediates to access serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-alanine transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination converts pyruvate to alanine, and later biochemical exchange with C1/C3 precursors yields serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-glycine hydroxymethyl route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis gives glycine, which in biochemical pools combines with C1/C3 intermediates to furnish serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN reservoir sustained glycine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide-formamide cycling sustains Strecker glycine production, which then enters biochemical serine assembly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cross-environment integrated route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent formate and glycolaldehyde feed surface triose and glycine chemistry, converging in prebiotic pools on serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Parallel pyruvate-glycerate convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry and surface glycerate chemistry independently form key intermediates that meet in biochemical serine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Serine", "overall_strategy": "The network targets serine through convergent production of central C1-C3 hubs across hydrothermal and surface settings, followed by prebiotic biochemical assembly. Hydrothermal vent chemistry supplies reduced carbon species such as formate, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, acetate, and pyruvate on iron-sulfur and oxide minerals. Surface cyanide, UV, borate, phosphate, sulfide-mineral, and clay chemistry converts these into aminonitriles, sugars, glycerate, and direct serine precursors. Biochemical-stage reactions connect pyruvate, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glycerate, formaldehyde, glycine, and alanine through transamination, Strecker-type capture, aldol chemistry, phosphorylation-linked oxidation equivalents, and wet-dry selection to yield multiple plausible routes to serine. Hub molecules are formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, glycine, and glycerate, each linking several reactions and enabling 10 distinct pathways to the same target.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O4", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "glyceric acid/glycerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O4/c4-1-2(5)3(6)7/h2,4-5H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "serine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(1-5)3(6)7/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide oxide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl equivalents that are released as formate.", "reasoning": "Iron-sulfur minerals are widely invoked as catalysts for hydrothermal CO2 fixation and formate generation under alkaline vent conditions; greigite and FeS phases are analogs of biological FeS centers and support prebiotic reduction chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing subseafloor hydrothermal setting"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of C1 oxyanions on reduced iron and oxide surfaces yields methanal/formaldehyde equivalents.", "reasoning": "Reduced iron and magnetite can promote stepwise CO2-derived C1 reduction under hydrothermal conditions; direct formaldehyde accumulation is context-dependent and partially speculative but is commonly used as a plausible C1 bridge between vent chemistry and surface sugar chemistry (Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015; speculative connector consistent with vent-to-surface transfer)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface UV cyanide-water chemistry to formamide and HCN reservoir", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, evaporitic concentration, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydrolysis/rearrangement of cyanide-derived species furnishes formamide as a concentrated nitrile-derived feedstock.", "reasoning": "HCN-derived photochemistry and formamide chemistry are widely considered important in surface prebiotic synthesis, especially under UV-active, anoxic conditions with photocatalytic minerals (Saladino et al., 2012; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface HCN photochemical regeneration", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photolysis and drying-rehydration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Photolytic fragmentation and dehydration of formamide-containing mixtures regenerate cyanide-bearing species including HCN.", "reasoning": "Surface photochemical networks interconvert cyanide and formamide pools, sustaining cyanide-rich feedstocks used in Strecker and nucleobase chemistry (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CO/CO2-H2 vent chemistry, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Surface-bound reduced C1 fragments undergo C-C coupling and partial oxygenation to yield a C2 aldehyde, glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type and related hydrothermal mineral catalysis can generate small oxygenated organics including aldehydes from reduced carbon feedstocks; glycolaldehyde as a vent-derived or vent-compatible C2 intermediate is plausible though product distributions vary (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface formose/aldol step to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles, mildly alkaline evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose chemistry couples formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to triose products, with borate stabilizing sugar intermediates.", "reasoning": "Borate-stabilized sugar formation from formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde is a classic route to trioses, and clays can concentrate organics during wet-dry cycles (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent gradients, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Reductive carboxylation and C-C assembly of activated acetyl/acetate-like intermediates generate the alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate and related central metabolites have been reported or proposed from nonenzymatic CO2 fixation and iron-catalyzed protometabolic networks under hydrothermal conditions (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "tr