ide is oversimplified and likely not cleanly bidirectional under one set of conditions. The glycine branch is decent; the serine endpoint remains insufficiently explicit.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Model formamide as a side reservoir rather than a simple reversible node with HCN.\",\n        \"Add hydrolysis and dehydration side chemistry if keeping the formamide branch.\",\n        \"Strengthen the final glycine-to-serine sequence with explicit chemistry.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.62,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.36\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.59,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.50,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.63,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the best conceptual cross-environment pathway because it clearly links hydrothermal C1/C2 production to surface sugar chemistry and then to biochemical assembly. Topologically it is strong, but chemically it still depends on uncertain hydrothermal glycolaldehyde production and an overly compressed final serine-forming reaction.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Preserve this as the backbone pathway but replace speculative end chemistry with explicit intermediates.\",\n        \"Consider adding glycolate, glycerate phosphate, or hydroxypyruvate nodes for realism.\",\n        \"Provide mineral agents for every hydrothermal and surface step.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.51,\n        \"rx