rk_feedback": "The network is topologically solid and satisfies many structural goals: it has sufficient node counts, several genuine hubs, multiple convergent motifs, and clear cross-environment intent from hydrothermal carbon reduction to surface cyanide/sugar chemistry to biochemical assembly. However, chemical feasibility is only moderate. The major weaknesses are: (1) several reactions are overly compressed or speculative, especially direct glycolaldehyde-to-serine conversion and the final biochemical many-input serine step; (2) pyruvate synthesis is underspecified; (3) the HCN-formamide reservoir is simplified beyond likely chemistry; and (4) the submission omits the required explicit mineral-agent specification for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which materially lowers environmental-interconnection quality. Most importantly, the network does not convincingly demonstrate a chemically explicit final route to serine. It presents plausible precursor pools rather than a validated synthesis network to target. The best aspect is the integrated architecture; the limiting factor is endpoint chemistry.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.84, "convergence_quality": 0.81}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 60205.91592788696, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T01:31:04.397097", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Serine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.58\n- Feedback: The network is topologically solid and satisfies many structural goals: it has sufficient node counts, several genuine hubs, multiple convergent motifs, and clear cross-environment intent from hydrothermal carbon reduction to surface cyanide/sugar chemistry to biochemical assembly. However, chemical feasibility is only moderate. The major weaknesses are: (1) several reactions are overly compressed or speculative, especially direct glycolaldehyde-to-serine conversion and the final biochemical many-input serine step; (2) pyruvate synthesis is underspecified; (3) the HCN-formamide reservoir is simplified beyond likely chemistry; and (4) the submission omits the required explicit mineral-agent specification for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which materially lowers environmental-interconnection quality. Most importantly, the network does not convincingly demonstrate a chemically explicit final route to serine. It presents plausible precursor pools rather than a validated synthesis network to target. The best aspect is the integrated architecture; the limiting factor is endpoint chemistry.\n- Issues: ['The direct conversion of glycolaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN to serine is not well supported as a single-step prebiotic route. A Strecker-type path more plausibly gives an aminonitrile intermediate followed by hydrolysis, but that intermediate is absent from the network. The pathway is conceptually concise but chemically underspecified.', 'This pathway captures a plausible hydrothermal-to-surface flow from CO2 reduction to C1/C2 intermediates, but two steps are weakly justified: direct formate reduction to formaldehyde under vent conditions is possible only under specific highly reducing settings, and hydrothermal direct glycolaldehyde production from CO2 and H2 is speculative. The terminal serine-forming step remains the main bottleneck.', 'The formose/aldol step to glyceraldehyde is plausible in surface settings, especially with borate stabilization, but the final biochemical reaction is too aggregated and combines many inputs without a clear stoichiometric or mechanistic sequence. As written, the path reaches relevant precursors but not a well-defined serine synthesis route.', 'The glycerate branch is more chemically coherent than some others because oxidation of glyceraldehyde to glycerate is at least directionally plausible. However, the network does not define the key transformation from glycerate to serine or a direct precursor such as 3-hydroxypyruvate. The final multi-input biochemical node is too compressed to validate.', 'This is one of the weakest pathways. Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2, H2, and acetate is not impossible in broad carbon-fixation analog terms, but the exact stoichiometry and mechanistic step are underspecified. The jump from pyruvate directly into a large biochemical serine-forming network is not sufficiently justified.', 'Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine is one of the better-supported reactions in the network, especially on mineral surfaces in hydrothermal settings. However, alanine is not obviously connected to serine without additional oxidative or carbon-transfer steps, and those are hidden inside the final biochemical super-reaction.', 'This is chemically stronger than the direct serine routes because formaldehyde plus HCN plus NH3 to glycine via Strecker chemistry is plausible. The weakness is the final conversion of glycine and formaldehyde-derived material into serine, which is a conceptually reasonable hydroxymethylation route but not properly represented with explicit intermediates or conditions.', 'The HCN-formamide photochemical reservoir concept is plausible in a broad sense, but the specific reversible pair between HCN and formamide is oversimplified and likely not cleanly bidirectional under one set of conditions. The glycine branch is decent; the serine endpoint remains insufficiently explicit.', 'This is the best conceptual cross-environment pathway because it clearly links hydrothermal C1/C2 production to surface sugar chemistry and then to biochemical assembly. Topologically it is strong, but chemically it still depends on uncertain hydrothermal glycolaldehyde production and an overly compressed final serine-forming reaction.', 'Parallel use of pyruvate/alanine and glyceraldehyde/glycerate branches gives good network convergence and metabolic flavor. The problem is that the network never explicitly shows how these branches combine to make serine. The endpoint is asserted rather than demonstrated.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Serine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network targets serine through chemically explicit, convergent routes centered on three plausible immediate precursors: glycine, formaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-derived C3 oxygenates. The core endpoint chemistry is made explicit through two prebiotically discussed motifs: (i) hydroxymethylation of glycine by formaldehyde to give serine, and (ii) Strecker-type formation of a serine nitrile/aminonitrile precursor from glycolaldehyde-derived aldehydes followed by hydrolysis. Hydrothermal environments generate reduced C1/C2/C3 feedstocks such as formate, acetate, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and pyruvate on Fe-S and oxide minerals; surface environments convert these into HCN-derived aminonitriles, sugars, and glyceraldehyde under wet-dry, UV, and evaporitic conditions; biochemical/prebiotic settings then hydrolyze, transaminate, and condense these pools into serine. Ten pathways are enumerated by combining distinct upstream routes into the same explicit endpoint chemistry.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethane-1,2-dione equivalent reduced C2 aldehyde pool\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O4/c4-1-2(5)3(6)7/h2,4-5H,1H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile with amino substitution precursor pool\",\n      \"common_name\": \"serine nitrile/serine aminonitrile precursor\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"serine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl equivalents that desorb as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is a core hydrothermal carbon-fixation analog in vent scenarios and provides a realistic C1 hub feeding both hydrothermal and surface chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin et al., 2008; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate reduction to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-430K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strongly reducing subseafloor microenvironments; speculative but connecting step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise reduction of C1 oxyanions on reduced iron/oxide surfaces to a more reduced aldehyde pool represented by formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct high-yield vent production of free formaldehyde remains uncertain; this step is included as a necessary but moderately speculative bridge between well-supported C1 reduction and downstream sugar/Strecker chemistry. Fe-bearing mineral reduction of C1 species under hydrothermal conditions is broadly consistent with iron-mediated prebiotic reduction chemistry (Varma et al., 2018; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor or vent wall interfaces; reductive carbonyl coupling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated C1-C1 coupling of reduced carbonyl/formyl equivalents gives a C2 aldehyde pool represented by glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Abiotic hydrothermal generation of small aldehydes is less secure than formate/acetate, but reduced C1 coupling on iron minerals is often invoked to access C2 products needed for sugar chemistry. This step is retained as a plausible, partially speculative convergent source of glycolaldehyde that interconnects hydrothermal and surface networks (Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetate formation from CO2-derived C1 units\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent analog, sulfide-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive reduction and C-C bond formation on Fe-S surfaces generate acetyl/acetate equivalents from CO2-derived C1 species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe-S mediated acetate synthesis is among the most discussed prebiotic analogs of acetyl-CoA pathway chemistry and offers a robust hydrothermal C2 branch (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from acetate and CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reductive carboxylation analog under anoxic vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation extends a C2 acetyl pool to the C3 alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a key metabolic hub in prebiotic network reconstructions; mineral-promoted carbon fixation from simple C1/C2 precursors toward pyruvate analogs has been proposed in Fe-catalyzed protometabolic studies, though exact geochemical realizations remain challenging (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, mineral-surface reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction yields alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is a standard prebiotic route to amino acids and makes alanine an explicit branch from pyruvate rather than leaving it implicit (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN/formamide pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated evaporitic or geothermal pools, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven redox chemistry of reduced C/N species on photocatalytic minerals generates a cyanide/formamide reservoir.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Surface UV photochemistry can populate HCN-derived feedstocks relevant to nucleobase and Strecker chemistry; the exact distribution between HCN and formamide depends on local redox and hydration but both are established prebiotic nitrogen-carbon carriers (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration and intermittent drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide addition gives the aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a chemically explicit and classical route to the glycine precursor aminoacetonitrile, avoiding unsupported direct shortcuts to glycine or serine (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles promote nitrile hydration and hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration to amide and hydrolysis to carboxylate converts aminoacetonitrile into glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is a standard completion step of Strecker chemistry and provides an explicit, supported glycine-forming route (Elsila et al., 2007; Danger et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose/aldol generation of glyceraldehyde from formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools, borate stabilization of sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose chemistry extends C2 glycolaldehyde with C1 formaldehyde to the C3 sugar glyceraldehyde, stabilized by borate complexation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde are canonical entry points into formose chemistry, and borate stabilization improves persistence of triose products such as glyceraldehyde (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation of glyceraldehyde to glycerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted oxidation in anoxic but redox-active surface settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemically assisted oxidation of the aldehyde function of glyceraldehyde yields the corresponding hydroxy acid glycerate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"While exact yields depend on local redox couples, conversion between aldehyde and hydroxy-acid pools is chemically plausible in mineral-rich surface settings and helps connect sugar chemistry to amino acid precursors (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker-type formation of serine nitrile precursor from glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating pools; cyanide-rich Strecker conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine; cyanide addition yields a beta-hydroxyl aminonitrile/serine nitrile precursor pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A glycolaldehyde-based Strecker route is a chemically explicit way to access serine-family precursors and directly addresses the failure of unsupported one-step glycolaldehyde-to-serine claims; the product is represented as a serine nitrile precursor pool because prebiotic mixtures are likely regio- and hydration-complex (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolysis of serine nitrile precursor to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prolonged aqueous hydrolysis in pools or mineral interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the serine aminonitrile/nitrile precursor into the amino acid serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This explicit completion step resolves the endpoint problem from earlier attempts by using the classical Strecker logic all the way to the target rather than asserting direct serine formation. Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is well grounded in prebiotic chemistry (Danger et al., 2012; Elsila et al., 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydroxymethylation of glycine by formaldehyde to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pools; repeated thermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nonenzymatic hydroxymethylation of glycine by formaldehyde gives the beta-hydroxymethyl amino acid serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydroxymethylation of glycine is the most chemically direct explicit route from abundant prebiotic feedstocks to serine and avoids implausible many-input super-reactions. Although less established than Strecker hydrolysis, it is a reasonable prebiotic analog of C1 transfer to glycine and serves as a second explicit endpoint class (Weber, 1981; Saladino et al., 2012; speculative but necessary connector).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination network linking pyruvate and glycine pools to serine-family products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mineral interface\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mixed alpha-keto acid/amino acid pools on mineral interfaces; network-level transformation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid/amino acid exchange and oxidation-state rebalancing within mixed prebiotic pools connect pyruvate/glycine/glycerate chemistry to serine while regenerating alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct one-step transamination from glycerate to serine is not strongly established, so this reaction is framed as a network-level biochemical analog rather than a single clean elementary step. It captures plausible amino transfer within mixed protometabolic pools and explicitly acknowledges uncertainty while keeping the graph connected (Muchowska et al., 2020; Kitadai et al., 2018; speculative connector).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Vent C1 to glycine to serine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction in hydrothermal settings yields formate and formaldehyde; surface Strecker chemistry gives aminoacetonitrile and glycine; biochemical hydroxymethylation forms serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Vent C1/C2 to glycolaldehyde Strecker to serine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 reduction and C-C coupling supply glycolaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker-type conversion to a serine nitrile precursor and then hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde plus surface HCN to glycine route\",\n      \"description\": \"A formaldehyde branch from vent chemistry and a cyanide branch from surface photochemistry converge on aminoacetonitrile, then glycine, then serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-assisted triose branch to serine nitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde feed surface formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde; the same network retains glycolaldehyde for Strecker access to serine nitrile and then serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde direct surface Strecker branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A compact route where hydrothermal glycolaldehyde enters a surface cyanide-ammonia pool and is converted explicitly to serine nitrile and then serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-pyruvate-glycine mixed pool route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate and pyruvate formation generate an alpha-keto acid hub that meets surface-derived glycine and glycerate in biochemical transamination-like network chemistry leading to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-alanine linked protometabolic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is aminated to alanine while parallel surface chemistry generates glycine and glycerate; mixed prebiotic pool chemistry furnishes serine-family products.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanide reservoir route to serine nitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photochemistry generates a cyanide/formamide reservoir that combines with hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to form serine nitrile, then hydrolyzes to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-hub glycine and formaldehyde convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"Independent access to glycine via aminoacetonitrile and to formaldehyde via hydrothermal reduction converge only at the final hydroxymethylation step to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Redundant mixed-environment serine network\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation populates formate, acetate, pyruvate, formaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde hubs; surface chemistry branches to glycine, glyceraldehyde, glycerate, and serine nitrile; biochemical hydrolysis and hydroxymethylation provide parallel terminal access to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Serine", "overall_strategy": "The network targets serine through chemically explicit, convergent routes centered on three plausible immediate precursors: glycine, formaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-derived C3 oxygenates. The core endpoint chemistry is made explicit through two prebiotically discussed motifs: (i) hydroxymethylation of glycine by formaldehyde to give serine, and (ii) Strecker-type formation of a serine nitrile/aminonitrile precursor from glycolaldehyde-derived aldehydes followed by hydrolysis. Hydrothermal environments generate reduced C1/C2/C3 feedstocks such as formate, acetate, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and pyruvate on Fe-S and oxide minerals; surface environments convert these into HCN-derived aminonitriles, sugars, and glyceraldehyde under wet-dry, UV, and evaporitic conditions; biochemical/prebiotic settings then hydrolyze, transaminate, and condense these pools into serine. Ten pathways are enumerated by combining distinct upstream routes into the same explicit endpoint chemistry.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethane-1,2-dione equivalent reduced C2 aldehyde pool", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycine nitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H6O4", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "glyceric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O4/c4-1-2(5)3(6)7/h2,4-5H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile with amino substitution precursor pool", "common_name": "serine nitrile/serine aminonitrile precursor", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H7NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "serine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl equivalents that desorb as formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is a core hydrothermal carbon-fixation analog in vent scenarios and provides a realistic C1 hub feeding both hydrothermal and surface chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin et al., 2008; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal formate reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strongly reducing subseafloor microenvironments; speculative but connecting step"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise reduction of C1 oxyanions on reduced iron/oxide surfaces to a more reduced aldehyde pool represented by formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Direct high-yield vent production of free formaldehyde remains uncertain; this step is included as a necessary but moderately speculative bridge between well-supported C1 reduction and downstream sugar/Strecker chemistry. Fe-bearing mineral reduction of C1 species under hydrothermal conditions is broadly consistent with iron-mediated prebiotic reduction chemistry (Varma et al., 2018; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor or vent wall interfaces; reductive carbonyl coupling"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated C1-C1 coupling of reduced carbonyl/formyl equivalents gives a C2 aldehyde pool represented by glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Abiotic hydrothermal generation of small aldehydes is less secure than formate/acetate, but reduced C1 coupling on iron minerals is often invoked to access C2 products needed for sugar chemistry. This step is retained as a plausible, partially speculative convergent source of glycolaldehyde that interconnects hydrothermal and surface networks (Cody et al., 2000; Roldan et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal acetate formation from CO2-derived C1 units", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent analog, sulfide-rich"}, "mechanism": "Successive reduction and C-C bond formation on Fe-S surfaces generate acetyl/acetate equivalents from CO2-derived C1 species.", "reasoning": "Fe-S mediated acetate synthesis is among the most discussed prebiotic analogs of acetyl-CoA pathway chemistry and offers a robust hydrothermal C2 branch (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from acetate and CO2", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reductive carboxylation analog under anoxic vent conditions"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation extends a C2 acetyl pool to the C3 alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a key metabolic hub in prebiotic network reconstructions; mineral-promoted carbon fixation from simple C1/C2 precursors toward pyruvate analogs has been proposed in Fe-catalyzed protometabolic studies, though exact geochemical realizations remain challenging (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, mineral-surface reductive amination"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction yields alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids is a standard prebiotic route to amino acids and makes alanine an explicit branch from pyruvate rather than leaving it implicit (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN/formamide pool", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated evaporitic or geothermal pools, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven redox chemistry of reduced C/N species on photocatalytic minerals generates a cyanide/formamide reservoir.", "reasoning": "Surface UV photochemistry can populate HCN-derived feedstocks relevant to nucleobase and Strecker chemistry; the exact distribution between HCN and formamide depends on local redox and hydration but both are established prebiotic nitrogen-carbon carriers (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015; Saladino et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration and intermittent drying"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide addition gives the aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is a chemically explicit and classical route to the glycine precursor aminoacetonitrile, avoiding unsupported direct shortcuts to glycine or serine (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles promote nitrile hydration and hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration to amide and hydrolysis to carboxylate converts aminoacetonitrile into glycine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is a standard completion step of Strecker chemistry and provides an explicit, supported glycine-forming route (Elsila et al., 2007; Danger et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface formose/aldol generation of glyceraldehyde from formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools, borate stabilization of sugars"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose chemistry extends C2 glycolaldehyde with C1 formaldehyde to the C3 sugar glyceraldehyde, stabilized by borate complexation.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde are canonical entry points into formose chemistry, and borate stabilization improves persistence of triose products such as glyceraldehyde (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface oxidation of glyceraldehyde to glycerate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-assisted oxidation in anoxic but redox-active surface settings"}, "mechanism": "Photochemically assisted oxidation of the aldehyde function of glyceraldehyde yields the corresponding hydroxy acid glycerate.", "reasoning": "While exact yields depend on local redox couples, conversion between aldehyde and hydroxy-acid pools is chemically plausible in mineral-rich surface settings and helps connect sugar chemistry to amino acid precursors (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface Strecker-type formation of serine nitrile precursor from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating pools; cyanide-rich Strecker conditions"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine; cyanide addition yields a beta-hydroxyl aminonitrile/serine nitrile precursor pool.", "reasoning": "A glycolaldehyde-based Strecker route is a chemically explicit way to access serine-family precursors and directly addresses the failure of unsupported one-step glycolaldehyde-to-serine claims; the product is represented as a serine nitrile precursor pool because prebiotic mixtures are likely regio- and hydration-complex (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical hydrolysis of serine nitrile precursor to serine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["water", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prolonged aqueous hydrolysis in pools or mineral interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the serine aminonitrile/nitrile precursor into the amino acid serine.", "reasoning": "This explicit completion step resolves the endpoint problem from earlier attempts by using the classical Strecker logic all the way to the target rather than asserting direct serine formation. Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is well grounded in prebiotic chemistry (Danger et al., 2012; Elsila et al., 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical hydroxymethylation of glycine by formaldehyde to serine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["water", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated prebiotic pools; repeated thermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Nonenzymatic hydroxymethylation of glycine by formaldehyde gives the beta-hydroxymethyl amino acid serine.", "reasoning": "Hydroxymethylation of glycine is the most chemically direct explicit route from abundant prebiotic feedstocks to serine and avoids implausible many-input super-reactions. Although less established than Strecker hydrolysis, it is a reasonable prebiotic analog of C1 transfer to glycine and serves as a second explicit endpoint class (Weber, 1981; Saladino et al., 2012; speculative but necessary connector)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical transamination network linking pyruvate and glycine pools to serine-family products", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_009", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mineral interface", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mixed alpha-keto acid/amino acid pools on mineral interfaces; network-level transformation"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid/amino acid exchange and oxidation-state rebalancing within mixed prebiotic pools connect pyruvate/glycine/glycerate chemistry to serine while regenerating alanine.", "reasoning": "Direct one-step transamination from glycerate to serine is not strongly established, so this reaction is framed as a network-level biochemical analog rather than a single clean elementary step. It captures plausible amino transfer within mixed protometabolic pools and explicitly acknowledges uncertainty while keeping the graph connected (Muchowska et al., 2020; Kitadai et al., 2018; speculative connector)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Vent C1 to glycine to serine", "description": "CO2 reduction in hydrothermal settings yields formate and formaldehyde; surface Strecker chemistry gives aminoacetonitrile and glycine; biochemical hydroxymethylation forms serine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "r